                "title": "Jeopardy! Part Ten",
                "body": "<p>The last semi-final, my second game. I&rsquo;m bouncing up and down on my toes behind the podium, almost laughing to myself, consciously aware of how eerily calm I&rsquo;m feeling, bracing for just how <em>fun</em> this next half hour is going to be. I can barely believe it myself, but the one conscious thought I remember having is of how relaxed I felt, moments before the intro music breaks the silence and the show starts.<em><br/></em></p>\n<p>It&rsquo;s a whirlwind of a game. I have a vague notion that I&rsquo;m ahead early on, that I seem to winning the buzzer fight, but not until Trebek lets me know (twice!) that I&rsquo;m off to a great start do I realize I&rsquo;m poised to actually win this game. Wow, I think to myself, maybe not letting the pressure and stress get to your head is the entire secret to being good at this game. Or maybe that I got to choose the first few categories that were my strengths helped. Or maybe playing Terry honed my buzzer skills more than Erika or Julia&rsquo;s games did for them! Who knows, and no time to think about it, I had to keep myself calm and stay on top of the game.</p>\n<p>That doesn&rsquo;t really work though. &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t think about elephants&rdquo; and you can&rsquo;t stop thinking about elephants.</p>\n<ul><li><span>The first half of the first round was kind of silly&ndash;pizza cutter? poncho? The one where I stretched my brain for a guess was Missouri, the Show Me State, possibly the only question in my entire Jeopardy! saga that I got because I&rsquo;d studied. </span></li>\n<li><span>My interview with Trebek&hellip; I wonder how many people noticed that 2000 crosswords in two years is exactly the 2 to 3 crosswords a day Trebek does&hellip;</span></li>\n<li><span>I absolutely would not have gotten &ldquo;Invisible Man&rdquo; if not for Erika&rsquo;s answer. And for one of the judge&rsquo;s shouting out &ldquo;No!&rdquo; after Trebek accepted &ldquo;The Invisible Man&rdquo; at first. And for Maggie using the exact example earlier that morning as one of the few examples where the article was important. Sorry Erika&hellip;</span></li>\n<li><span>&ldquo;Clever&rdquo; guesses in the Double Jeopardy! round: I guess people keep asking me how I knew &ldquo;metadata&rdquo;, which guess sort of supports my point that the vast majority of people really don&rsquo;t match Reddit&rsquo;s obsession with the NSA? And I knew about Yap&rsquo;s giant stone wheels because of Rich Hall&rsquo;s short speech on an episode of QI, marking the only clue on Jeopardy! that watching a hundred episodes of QI helped me with.</span></li>\n<li><span>I&rsquo;m irrationally sad that I didn&rsquo;t get the Hundred Years&rsquo; War clue. That is my pet subject. :(</span></li>\n<li><span>When I saw &ldquo;whale&rdquo; and &ldquo;singing&rdquo; in the same clue, &ldquo;Baby Beluga&rdquo; instantly came to mind and I buzzed in with &gt;95% certainty in my head that I was right with &ldquo;Beluga&rdquo;. I guess that&rsquo;s what happens if you play Jeopardy! like a word association game.</span></li>\n</ul><p><span>After the Yap clue, I looked up and saw the scores were 13,000 to 5,600 and 7,800, and I realized I had an enormous chance of winning. Or at least going into Final with a lead. Less than three categories were left on the board. I definitely thought, &ldquo;I could probably keep the lead even if I didn&rsquo;t answer anything.&rdquo; It was probably a bad idea to have that thought, especially since there was still a Daily Double up, because the complacency shut my brain down. I couldn&rsquo;t recall two of the music questions that I definitely knew. But even as their scores kept going up, I was thinking to myself, &ldquo;if they keep dividing the points evenly, I&rsquo;m going to win.&rdquo; A couple triple-stumpers went by, and I felt even better about my chances. I half-tried to buzz in on &ldquo;Sandra Day O'Connor&rdquo; but Erika beat me to it and took the negative. And that&rsquo;s how I didn&rsquo;t even buzz in once in the last half of Double Jeopardy!.</span></p>\n<p><span>And then it was Final, and I was in the lead, and I felt the small bit of relief that my bet-to-win was already chosen for me. Shakespeare Characters comes up, and I briefly run through all the characters I can think of. Macbeth, Macduff, Hamlet, Ophelia, Leander, Othello and Desdemonda and Iago, Katherine, Prospero, etc. and etc., a long mental list in my head. Somehow, I fool myself into thinking I know the majority of the characters. Maggie came to talk to and congratulate us, Glenn stood next to my podium and made me second and third and fourth-guess my wager, and then the clue came up.</span></p>\n<p><span>Oh my god. I know this. It&rsquo;s Falstaff. Could it possibly be anything else? No, it has to be Falstaff, I can name the three plays.</span></p>\n<p><span>Even as certain as I was, I couldn&rsquo;t relax (when did I stop relaxing?). I&rsquo;m not finally sure that I&rsquo;ve won until Trebek confirms Julia&rsquo;s correct answer. My poker face is terrible, but I&rsquo;m trying to give a face that might be misconstrued as extreme disappointment in myself.</span></p>\n<p><span>It&rsquo;s become one of the greatest regrets in my life that I didn&rsquo;t turn and shake Erika and Julia&rsquo;s hands before walking over to Trebek, that I couldn&rsquo;t acknowledge how great the game was, that all I could manage was a glance over as I was already walking, a &ldquo;sorry for winning&rdquo; shrug.</span></p>\n<p><span>God, I hate winning. I seriously, genuinely prefer losing a game to feeling like a showboater and watching other people lose. My favorite outcomes are ones where I play hard and prove my aptitude or prowess, but then step aside to luck or a misstep and let someone else win.</span></p>\n<p><span>So I guess that&rsquo;ll lead us into the last two games, to be continued!</span></p>",
