                    "comment": "<p>Ugh, nine parts&hellip;</p>\n<p>There were fewer people on the bus the next day, which was saddening. But there was more talking on the bus. I was outright jealous that people were finding connections between each other; quidditch, mutual friends, TV shows, etc. I had a &nbsp;book of one-page biographies in my bag the entire day, but I never took it out to study with for sake of being&nbsp;<em>that guy</em>.</p>\n<p>Throughout the morning the atmosphere of the group was incredibly relaxed. We&rsquo;d all agreed on the bus how almost all the stifling pressure from yesterday was gone; only one in three of us was moving on.</p>\n<p>The single highlight of the morning for me was when, during rehearsal, a clue came up for &ldquo;Blah blah blah blah this country with capital city Canberra&rdquo; and I said &ldquo;What is Canada?&rdquo;. In an attempt to bluff my opponents. Into thinking I was inept. It should say something that this is the one thing that stuck with me.</p>\n<p>How bad would it have been if I&rsquo;d done that on national TV?</p>\n<p>The first three competitors go up and the rest of us take our seats in the audience. We laughed at &ldquo;avada kedavra&rdquo; going to Tucker and not Laurie. I remember it being a very intense game, with all three of them having incredibly close scores throughout and each having more than 10k going into final. The six of us in the audience have to point with amazement at the scores. Then the next three are called away and until Tucker, Laurie, and Whitney come back, it&rsquo;s just me, Erika, and Julia in the audience, smiling awkwardly.</p>\n<p>The next game is equally tense, although Ben and Eric make the audience laugh with their antics. Still, going into Final it is a very high scoring and close game, but Erika, Julia and I are led away before the last clue comes up.</p>\n<p>It&rsquo;s just the three of us, in the dressing room, getting makeup done and listening to a pep talk from Maggie. I genuinely feel relaxed, loose, almost liberated. I remember being shocked at how unstressed I felt, even as Maggie announces that it&rsquo;s showtime. We wish each other good luck before we&rsquo;re led out in a row onto the now-familiar stage for the last semifinal match.</p>"
