                "title": "Jeopardy! Part 8",
                "body": "<p><span>After the game, I was in a bit of a daze. Voices were telling me I did well, that I&rsquo;d played a good game, but my thoughts were missing in action. I was coming down from a high, gathering my wits, collecting my marbles. I don&rsquo;t remember if I walked to lunch with Kenesha and Maggie, or if Terry was there too, or if the whole group walked over, or anything at all. My mind was utterly exhausted.</span></p>\n<p>The first real thing I remember after the game was talking to Cameron at the cafeteria, while we both got food. Cameron congratulated me (not for winning, of course) and told me my score was the highest so far. I asked him about his game, which he was humble about, a bit dejected but still hopeful of moving on. It was the first I&rsquo;d really talked to any of the contestants.</p>\n<p>The next thing I remember is having massive stomach pains while trying to eat some kind of Asian fried noodles. So my body and my mind had had trouble reacting to the situation. Physiological symptoms of extreme stress, I guess. Or a spontaneous stomach ulcer. I sat at a long table with all nine contestants who had played so far and listened to people talk about their games. I also tried to make some small talk with Terry and Kenesha at lunch, but neither seemed to feel much like talking either.</p>\n<p>I only remember a few other events from the rest of the day (god I wish I had written this stuff down sooner). I watched the other two games intently, having never seen an episode from the audience before. I watched Laurie and Tucker&rsquo;s intense reactions to the end of the fifth quarterfinal from the row behind them. And then at the end of the day, after we gathered our gift bags, we got a rousing round of applause from our parents as we filed out of the studio doors into the Sony backlot.</p>\n<p>Then lastly, I remember an endless (not quite banal, but endless) bus ride back to our hotel. This is when my brain finally had a long chance to reflect on the events of the day, and I found I was more than satisfied. I was already happy just to be on the show, to get my chance to play Jeopardy!, to fulfill a longtime dream. I wasn&rsquo;t disqualified, my episode was (presumably) going to air, and that in itself was enough&ndash;playing in the semi-finals tomorrow was just an added treat.</p>\n<p>The atmosphere in the bus was genial, even though I think most of the others were also silently going over the day&rsquo;s events.</p>\n<p>My dad and I ate (antisentimentally) in the Universal City food court for dinner. He had nothing but praise and pride for me. I kept looking to see if I&rsquo;d see anyone else from Jeopardy! down there, because I did sort of feel like that would nice, to have an incredibly simple way to start a conversation with any of the people I&rsquo;d met that day.</p>\n<p>I had nothing emotionally riding on my game tomorrow&ndash;all I had to do was try not to end in the negatives, make a fool of myself, swear on TV, fall off the stage, etc. and I could really leave LA proud of myself. Where I was a ball of stress just 24 hours earlier, I could almost say I was relaxed that night. I even let myself watch a few episodes of Law and Order: SVU on the hotel TV&ndash;the ultimate kill-time-instead-of-sleeping show.</p>\n<p>Still, I looked through some old Jeopardy! clues before I called it a night.</p>",
