                "title": "Jeopardy! Part 7",
                "body": "<p>Let&rsquo;s talk about the game.</p>\n<p>Terry, Kenesha, and I are led out to the stage, the third game of the day. My chest and head are pounding. There are some cheers from the audience as the three of us take our positions. Maggie and Glenn are still hanging around, telling us to write our names down, giving us advice, keeping us calm. I don&rsquo;t believe any of it&rsquo;s real, and I don&rsquo;t think I&rsquo;m having very many coherent emotional reactions. Sensory overstimulation? Whatever happened, my brain really isn&rsquo;t taking anything in.</p>\n<p>We get some final instructions, what cameras to look at, smile, have fun, and then suddenly the stage is empty and the set is almost silent. I take deep breaths, try to calm myself down, lower the volume of my pounding heart. Then I see Trebek himself standing behind the game board, holding his bandaged wrist in front, looking almost shyly out from behind the board. It is the cherry on top of the entire surreal experience so far. Being on set, standing behind the podium, seeing myself on a screen in the position of a Jeopardy! contestant&ndash;all of this was strange enough. But seeing Trebek&ndash;instead of as a perfect TV host, always standing in the correct spot, saying the correct thing&ndash;seeing him standing there, looking out at us as an actual human being? That was the weirdest feeling.</p>\n<p>I guess that kind of thing is pretty common when people meet celebrities. For the last few moments, I find myself wondering how Trebek hurt his arm.</p>\n<p>The music starts, the music that will make my adrenaline surge to this day. And then the next forty minutes go by in what feels like five, or one. Even with the commercial breaks, it is extremely difficult to recall what happened at all, and the first time I saw the episode, almost everything was new to me except for the end result.</p>\n<p>Stray observations:</p>\n<ul><li>I&rsquo;d wished for a category like Prime Numbers, and for the sake of my reputation, I jumped to it immediately and at every opportunity. Of course, I don&rsquo;t manage to buzz on a single one of the five. For the largest three-digit prime, I was factoring 997 in my head and had gotten to 13 before I realized there was no way they wanted me to actually factor it. Kenesha buzzed in a split second before me. I still haven&rsquo;t lived that down.</li>\n<li>The break was the first time I looked at my score, to my shock I was at $0. (I didn&rsquo;t remember I had hit $0 until months later when I was reading tweets about how the Asian guy had no money.) I wasn&rsquo;t particularly nervous, but I started to lose a bit of my self-confidence, realizing that I was against two obviously strong competitors who were destroying me on the buzzer, and that my advancing to the semifinals was fairly uncertain.</li>\n<li>Telling the story to Trebek (and I guess the rest of the country) was terrifying. I&rsquo;m surprised I didn&rsquo;t turn crimson. Trebek just let me roll with it and gave me a nice little out for an ending. Thanks, Trebek, for doing what you do.</li>\n<li>I&rsquo;m incredibly proud I got <em>Breakfast of Champions </em>it right. It could have been the only clue I got right the whole tournament and I&rsquo;d be pretty stoked.</li>\n<li>I desperately wished the <em>Leaves of Grass</em> DD was mine when Trebek read it out. One of the things I&rsquo;d wanted to do on the show was to prove that as a math major I still knew random things from literature and history. </li>\n<li>The interesting guesses I got in Double Jeopardy! were chainsaw (got a lot of comments about that one, felt brilliant for pulling it out of my head) and Jennifer Garner. While I was watching myself for the first time, I saw the clue and thought &ldquo;the woman who played Alias, but I don&rsquo;t know who that is&rdquo;, then &ldquo;WHAT THE HELL&rdquo; when I got it.</li>\n</ul><p>After the last clue (or during, since I had no idea), I looked up at the scores and saw to my surprise that I was actually in contention. Kenesha had played valiantly but guessed too much in Double Jeopardy!. I could actually win if Terry got it wrong and I bet intelligently. But then the Final category came up, and my head hit the podium in exasperation. Bible Characters, near the top on my short list of unwanted categories. You can see Trebek glance over at the my small commotion.</p>\n<p>But the clue came up, and the answer came to mind early, and there was no doubt in my mind it was right. I hold my breath at the possibility Terry might have gotten it wrong, but when her correct answer appears, it oddly comes as a bit of a relief. When I step off the stage, all of my pent up vigor evaporates, and I feel exhausted.</p>",
