                "title": "Solutions #168 - 170",
                "body": "<div>\n<p>Oh jeez, these problems are two years old. I&rsquo;ll link the problems in the problem numbers, because I think these problems are definitely worth looking at.</p>\n</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"http://ivoirians.tumblr.com/post/29494570742/problem-168-king-duel\">168:</a> a. Bruce can legitimately win on a 2x2 board. If he places the two kings on squares of the same color, Alfred can never win, because his move will always bring him to the opposite color, while Bruce will always be on the same color after his move.</p>\n<p>b. Alfred takes at most 7 moves to get to the same row as Bruce. From there, he takes at most 7 more moves to get to the same column as Bruce, while staying in the same row. He can win in less than 14 moves.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://ivoirians.tumblr.com/post/29841324731/problem-169-farey\">169.</a> Here are your examples:</p>\n<p>phi(1) = 1, phi(2) = 1, phi(3) = 2, phi(4) = 2, phi(5) = 4, phi(6) = 2, &hellip;</p>\n<p>So for n = 5, our N numbers are 1, 2, 3, 3, 4, 4, 5, 5, 5, 5. A sequence that works is 1 5 4 3 5 2 5 3 4 5. 1/5 + 1/20 + 1/12 + 1/15 + 1/10 + 1/10 + 1/15 + 1/12 + 1/20 + 1/5 = 1.</p>\n<p>So let&rsquo;s use induction. We have 1/1 = 1. Assume we have some sequence a1, a2, &hellip; aN that satisfies the equation. We have to add in phi(n+1) terms, all n+1, and have it still satisfy the equation. How do we do this?</p>\n<p>Maybe it would help to show you how the sequence for n = 4 looks. 1 4 3 2 3 4 gives &frac14; + 1/12 + 1/6 + 1/6 + 1/12 + &frac14; = 1.</p>\n<p>Note that when we move from 4 to 5, all we did was insert 5s into this sequence. Where do they go? Well, if we insert n in between a and b, we get 1/an + 1/nb = (b + a)/(abn). This is equal to 1/ab if and only if b+a = n. So we insert n anywhere we have a + b = n, and the sequence will still add up to one.</p>\n<p>How many places are there in the sequence where consecutive terms add up to n? What do you know, it happens to be phi(n).</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://ivoirians.tumblr.com/post/30185832131/problem-170-cannibals\">170.</a> If there were only one cannibal, he would eat Nathaniel. If there were two cannibals, both know that if either eats Nathaniel, he will be eaten by the other cannibal immediately.</p>\n<p>Recursively, we see that if there are an even number of cannibals, no one will eat Nathaniel. If there are an odd number, the closest cannibal will eat him, and then no one else will dare.</p>\n</blockquote>",
