                "title": "Jeopardy! Part 6",
                "body": "<p>As I expect my readers to understand, I am often months late on regularly scheduled posts.</p>\n<p>I&rsquo;d showered, dressed, and mentally prepped a full hour before I had to go down to the lobby. Yet I was surprised at how calm I felt. This was the day, the big day, I&rsquo;d been waiting months for this day. Who knew what would happen in the next twelve hours? I think I was suppressing my thoughts lest I go crazy before I even make it to the studio.</p>\n<p>Skip ahead a bit. I think a girl wearing a green dress but not wearing a college sweatshirt was also waiting for the elevator, and a girl wearing a Harvard sweatshirt got on a few floors below. No one said a word. I didn&rsquo;t even look at them, just sort of grinned so they might know I understood the awkwardness of this elevator ride.</p>\n<p>Cut to the hotel lobby, where around fifteen students and most of their parents are standing in a circle making small talk with each other. I fall into the familiar habit of not saying a word and listening to others like a good introvert. This is where I get my first good look at most of the other competitors. You could tell Jeopardy! selected for a very bright and attractive group, which made me feel a bit proud to be included, but also inevitably self-conscious.</p>\n<p>Onto the bus, where I sit by myself, thinking I could have brought a bag like everyone else. Maggie keeps us enthralled for most of the trip. She&rsquo;s absolutely amazing, and I&rsquo;ve been telling myself to send her an e-mail just thanking her for everything she did and the whole experience, but it doesn&rsquo;t feel like the right time yet. I watch LA pass by, still looking for some last minute tidbits of trivia to pick up from billboards or restaurant signs. No dice. I pick up a sample question Maggie gives from Entourage -&gt; Ari -&gt; Arizona, something picked up via a very common crossword clue, and something most of the bus seemed to not know, so I feel like that&rsquo;s a solid start to the day.</p>\n<p>A whirlwind of a morning. Hanging out in the green room, signing forms, getting makeup, listening to Maggie&rsquo;s enthralling speeches. They call us in small groups outside to record some interviews, and I&rsquo;m the last person they call. Glenn leads me past the life-size cutout of Trebek and around the corner, and suddenly, I&rsquo;m on set. I can see the giant game board, the podiums, the tastefully colored backgrounds (technically this is a set I&rsquo;ve never seen before on TV, but the features are there). The cameras, the rows of seats for the audience, the judges&rsquo; and producers&rsquo; tables. I desperately want to take pictures.</p>\n<p>More of a blur. All of us gather behind the podiums to hear more about the game. The screens, the buzzers, the view of the game board and the cameras. It is incredibly surreal. There isn&rsquo;t any other way to describe it. You almost never see more than four people on set, and it feels like such a controlled and tight operation on TV, but now suddenly you see technicians and cameramen and producers walking around, adjusting things, talking to each other. It&rsquo;s freaky. Maybe what gets to me the most is I can look wherever I want. I can stare at the gameboard, or the backdrop, and admire its size and the colors for as long as I want, not just while the camera is focused on it. What a random thing to be impressed by! I guess it just hammered home how lucky I was to be where I was.</p>\n<p>Rehearsal heightens how eerie it feels, to be pushing the buzzer, shouting out &ldquo;What is&hellip;&rdquo; answers, <em>playing the game</em>. My inner self shuddered when I answer my first question, but then my brain takes over and leave no room for raw emotions. Playing Jeopardy! in person demands your full attention. No room for feelings, no room for worrying or feeling nervous or self-conscious, no room for even recording memories, it seems.</p>\n<p>We&rsquo;re led into the green room to await the first game. I play Jenga to ease my nerves, but it turns out that Jenga only makes people even more high-strung. Shaun of the Dead goes up on the TV, and having never seen it, I half-watch it, half try to suppress my internal panic. I&rsquo;m thinking, how do I not panic, how do I not make a fool of myself on television, how do I memorize more information in these last hours? Another three people are called out. The remaining students try to make light of the situation. The alternates, Gus and Sam, are the least nervous by far and helping to keep us all sane, to which I must be forever grateful.</p>\n<p>Almost exactly at the end of the movie, Maggie comes in and announces Kenesha, Terry, and I will be playing the last game before lunch. Three of the quiet people, who know nothing about each other at this point. I feel calmer than I expected, but that might have been a delusion at this point! I&rsquo;m thinking purely in aphorisms, relevant or not, as my brain diverts all of its raw computational power to playing the game. Cares to the wind, balls to the wall, no guts no glory, make it or break it, no turning back now, as the three of us are led past the Trebek cardboard cutout, around the corner, and onto the set.</p>",
