                "title": "Jeopardy! Part 5",
                "body": "<p>On the way to the airport, I realized I&rsquo;d left behind two things: my old cell phone, which might have been needed to prove the veracity of one of my interview questions; and my I &lt;3 Math wristband. The first was negligible&ndash;Alex could just take my word that I&rsquo;d used one cell phone for 11 years (what a great story, am I right or am I right). But we straight up delayed my flight for the wristband, which I&rsquo;d worn almost every day for five years. It wasn&rsquo;t superstition (maybe it sort of was), I simply didn&rsquo;t feel comfortable or whole without that wristband on. And maybe luck would matter.</p>\n<p>My dad (I can&rsquo;t keep saying mother and father, who am I trying to kid) left first on an earlier flight while I read a book (365 biographies about important people throughout history, none of whom would make an appearance in the next week). I had my mind set on taking as many pictures as I could of every step this week&ndash;this was truly, in every sense, a once in a lifetime trip. But I guess I&rsquo;m pretty absent-minded, because I have almost no pictures to show for it.</p>\n<p>Got to LA, took a taxi to the hotel located on top of a hill next to Universal Studios. We checked in, went to our room, and then&hellip; the next 36 hours are totally uneventful. We ate dinner the first night at Bubba Gump&rsquo;s, because I was feeling touristy and a little spendthrift-y. Our future meals would mostly come from the food court. I didn&rsquo;t have much of an urge to see LA. I stayed in, watched TV, watched the 2013 College Championship (which I&rsquo;d saved for this day, to give me the closest reading on what I could expect tomorrow). Set alarms for fifteen minute increments from 5:30 to 7:00am. Went to sleep at midnight, mostly calm if only if I had no idea what to expect the next day.</p>\n<p>I feel like I&rsquo;m writing my autobiography. And that&rsquo;s a pretty presumptuous act, documenting your rather mundane life and assuming people will care. I&rsquo;m going to maintain that I&rsquo;m just writing this for myself, and I swear this will be the last time I awkwardly explain myself.</p>",
