                        "content": "<p>On the way to the airport, I realized I’d left behind two things: my old cell phone, which might have been needed to prove the veracity of one of my interview questions; and my I <3 Math wristband. The first was negligible–Alex could just take my word that I’d used one cell phone for 11 years (what a great story, am I right or am I right). But we straight up delayed my flight for the wristband, which I’d worn almost every day for five years. It wasn’t superstition (maybe it sort of was), I simply didn’t feel comfortable or whole without that wristband on. And maybe luck would matter.</p>\n<p>My dad (I can’t keep saying mother and father, who am I trying to kid) left first on an earlier flight while I read a book (365 biographies about important people throughout history, none of whom would make an appearance in the next week). I had my mind set on taking as many pictures as I could of every step this week–this was truly, in every sense, a once in a lifetime trip. But I guess I’m pretty absent-minded, because I have almost no pictures to show for it.</p>\n<p>Got to LA, took a taxi to the hotel located on top of a hill next to Universal Studios. We checked in, went to our room, and then… the next 36 hours are totally uneventful. We ate dinner the first night at Bubba Gump’s, because I was feeling touristy and a little spendthrift-y. Our future meals would mostly come from the food court. I didn’t have much of an urge to see LA. I stayed in, watched TV, watched the 2013 College Championship (which I’d saved for this day, to give me the closest reading on what I could expect tomorrow). Set alarms for fifteen minute increments from 5:30 to 7:00am. Went to sleep at midnight, mostly calm if only if I had no idea what to expect the next day.</p>\n<p>I feel like I’m writing my autobiography. And that’s a pretty presumptuous act, documenting your rather mundane life and assuming people will care. I’m going to maintain that I’m just writing this for myself, and I swear this will be the last time I awkwardly explain myself.</p>",
