                "title": "Jeopardy! Part 4",
                "body": "<p><span>I can&rsquo;t wait to write future posts, but this part reads a little dry, IMO.</span></p>\n<p><span>For two months, I studied pretty intensely for my impending Jeopardy! appearance. My first stop the day after I got home was the local library. I planned to devour almanacs and general knowledge books. Books like </span><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/An-Incomplete-Education-Learned-Probably/dp/0345468902\">&ldquo;An Incomplete Education&rdquo;</a><span> and </span><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/York-Times-Guide-Essential-Knowledge/dp/0312643020\">&ldquo;The New York Times Guide to Essential Knowledge&rdquo;</a><span>. Great books, books that held a tremendous wealth of information: German opera composers to French Modernist painters, Academy Award winning films to constellations, Supreme Court cases to Baseball Hall of Famers. Everything you could imagine would ever appear in a Jeopardy! question.</span></p>\n<p>On one hand, it was tremendously foolish to think I&rsquo;d be able to get through the tomes, and it turned out to be silly to think it would help at all. On the other, I definitely rekindled my love of trivia in those few weeks.</p>\n<p>As a child, I&rsquo;d absorbed books. I remember three specific books that I read religiously: a trivia book with 1000 (5000? 10000) fun facts, &ldquo;The Twentieth Century, Year by Year&rdquo; (a huge coffee table book with a two-page spread for each of the hundred years), and the dictionary. I seriously loved reading the dictionary, finding new words, adding to the knowledge in my belt. I was an information addict. All of that waned as my responsibilities in the real world increased, but I guess that&rsquo;s the answer to all the &ldquo;how do you know so much stuff?&rdquo; questions I get&ndash;I devoured information from a very young age.</p>\n<p>So the studying process was like a nostalgia trip. It&rsquo;d been a while since I&rsquo;d just sat down and enjoyed the drug that is raw information, trivia, stats, figures, facts. I hadn&rsquo;t even seen the show Jeopardy! since high school.</p>\n<p>But then one problem cropped up: I&rsquo;d now completely lost the ability to retain the knowledge I acquired. On something as simple as the world capitals, I&rsquo;d drill myself on a small number of countries and half an hour later be completely unable to remember any of their capitals. If I&rsquo;d set my mind to it when I was younger, memorizing all of the capitals would have taken less than a day of focused study, as it was with state capitals, digits of pi, or elements of the periodic table. This was worrying both in regards to Jeopardy! and the state of my brain&ndash;was my potential for learning done? Was my method of studying flawed, or should I somehow not have wasted all the space in my head?</p>\n<p>I also watched plenty of old episodes and played plenty of practice games on j-archive. I realized a) I would have fared much better as a high-schooler, when all the history and biology and literature was fresh in my head and when I still had my memory fully intact, and b) the game is a lot harder than you remember. I definitely used to think that I had 90% of the questions on Jeopardy! down while I was playing along in front of the TV. It&rsquo;s not till you start playing seriously and tracking your performance that you realize how quickly you forget about and disregard those Broadway theater or art history or 1950s television categories that utterly stump you. You take your wordplay category and your high school knowledge categories and run both of them, and you think the game is easy. But noo. Here comes British Royalty or Russian playwrights or Phoenicia to mess your day up. On the show, you can&rsquo;t just pretend a category doesn&rsquo;t exist.</p>\n<p>Either way, let&rsquo;s get to my final point: cramming was totally inefficient. Jeopardy! is unfathomably fast, primarily because if you&rsquo;re buzzing in, you&rsquo;ve read the whole clue and jumped on an answer (question) in less time than it takes Trebek to read the clue aloud. Except for maybe two or three of them, every single answer (question) I gave was something I&rsquo;d known for years and could recall instantly. Lists of Supreme Court justices and even world capitals never came to mind.<em><br/></em></p>\n<p>So my weeks of studying were mostly for naught, but I suppose I may have reviewed the information I did know, strengthened those connections in my head. And at least I got to relive the joy of trivia before I went on the show.</p>",
