                    "comment": "<p>We&rsquo;re going to step up the pace if I want to get to Part 10 in any reasonable amount of time. I&rsquo;m sorry to any followers who really just wanted math problems, and now they&rsquo;re getting long and banal recounts of my personal life. I don&rsquo;t really have any non-ego-related reasons for posting this on the internet. Maybe someone wants to read these? Maybe posting them for everyone to see forces me to try and write better? Who knows. It&rsquo;s probably just my ego; I&rsquo;ve always abused my math blog as an outlet for personal problems. This is an invitation to unfollow me if you don&rsquo;t want another 8 parts of this story on your Tumblr wall/timeline/whatever.</p>\n<p>What would part 3 be? The day I got the call? Time to retell things I barely remember again. Some time in November (did I mention the audition was in June? God damn I&rsquo;m bad at storytelling). The Monday before Thanksgiving break. I get out of the shower and I walk to my room in my towel. I check my phone and find I&rsquo;ve gotten a missed call in the last ten minutes. Unknown number, random area code&ndash;but they left a voice mail.</p>\n<p>&ldquo;Hello, this is Robert James from Jeopardy!&hellip;&rdquo;</p>\n<p>Oh jesus. I don&rsquo;t even think to put on pants before calling back.</p>\n<p>(It&rsquo;d be awesome if I could recount exactly what we said to each other on the phone. For the narrative. But I can&rsquo;t. It&rsquo;s been too long.)</p>\n<p>Robert is clearly toying with me. I can hear him on the verge of laughing at me through the phone, as I stand there in the middle of my room, pacing, concentrating on every answer I give. Have I ever appeared on Jeopardy! with Alex Trebek? Does anyone in my family work for Sony Pictures Studios? Am I a college student, am I a felon? No, no, no, no, get to the point, Robert, I&rsquo;m having a heart attack here.</p>\n<p>&ldquo;How are you feeling, Kevin?&rdquo; (Ugh I wish I could quote him verbatim.)</p>\n<p>&ldquo;I gotta be honest, I&rsquo;m kinda freaking out here, Robert.&rdquo; I can&rsquo;t stop grinning.</p>\n<p>He laughs. &ldquo;How would you like to be on Jeopardy!?&rdquo;</p>\n<p>A beat. &ldquo;I&rsquo;d love to!&rdquo;</p>\n<p>&ldquo;Well, we&rsquo;d love to have you, Kevin.&rdquo;</p>\n<p>The rest of the phone call is a blur. He tells me he&rsquo;ll send an e-mail to me later, and to not go crazy telling everyone I know yet, and I think to let him know if I get any interview requests. And then he hangs up, and I&rsquo;m just in my room, in my boxers, jumping up and down in excitement. I must have looked ridiculous. Lucky my roommate already went to class.</p>\n<p>Okay let&rsquo;s be fair I jumped up and down like once or twice and then put on pants I&rsquo;m not a loony loon here.</p>\n<p>I succeed in going the rest of the day without telling a soul. Just a massive secret hanging over my head. I&rsquo;ve already decided my family will be the first to hear it in person when I go home for Thanksgiving. Then, a former best friend from Yale, and another close friend from Yale, and a friend from UPenn, and then that&rsquo;s it. I don&rsquo;t want to tell anyone because who knows what will happen, what if they find out they called the wrong person or Jeopardy! gets canceled or I miss my flight out to the taping or I die in an ironic accident? Oh my god, what if I die before I can tell anyone? What if no one ever knows? I am suddenly terrified of dying, this is no joke. I have to take the train and then drive home the next day and the entire time I am freaking out about crashing or derailing or an earthquake or an aneurysm or an airstrike prematurely ending my Jeopardy! dreams. The fear of death has been reinstilled in me, big time. I might have prayed for my survival.</p>\n\n<p>I don&rsquo;t even tell my mother on the drive home. She asks a few times if I have any big news and I say I don&rsquo;t. We get some dinner and it&rsquo;s not until we&rsquo;re all in the living room that I spring it on them, and then we&rsquo;re all group hugging and going nuts. I don&rsquo;t think I&rsquo;d ever had my family feel more proud for me (go ahead and psychoanalyze me, Freud). And then after ten minutes we&rsquo;re back to normal. Except that my mother is obsessively googling everything she can about Jeopardy! on her computer.</p>\n<p>I tell a few friends at Berkeley the week I get back from Thanksgiving (maybe five of them total), The rest of my friends don&rsquo;t find out I&rsquo;m on Jeopardy! until well after the taping date. Which I guess is Part five because I have to talk about studying for some reason? Ugh ugh ugh ugh ugh. Part six will be where the fun starts. And I might have to extend this to twelve parts. Gonna milk this last of my fifteen minutes for everything it&rsquo;s worth, before life goes back to normal.</p>"
