                        "content_raw": "<p>The audition really doesn't merit it's own full post. It'd just be a recap of an ancient event I kind of sort of remember. It might be more useful to jump to part 6 and get my most recent thoughts down before they cool off. But this ain't gonna be no Slaughterhouse-Five.</p>\r\n<p>There isn't a ton to talk about, or maybe I've already forgotten it all. I got to the hotel, joined the fifteen or so awkwardly milling around people in the upstairs foyer, and pretended to have something engrossing to do on my phone. I think I did a crossword. One guy showed up wearing a Cal polo, so of course I went way out of my comfort zone and said hi to him. Another Cal student also showed up, so we had a small chat before Robert came out and started taking our pictures.</p>\r\n<p>During Robert and Corina's extremely high-energy speech at us, I remember looking around and scoping out the College competition. It was somewhat depressing how capable everyone seemed. They seemed confident, sociable, bright, and definitely had an average of 3 points on me in looks. There were around five tall, blond athletes of both genders. Wasn't this just the audition? Didn't completely un-TV friendly people get into the audition too? A couple other Asian guys, and I think there weren't any Asian girls (would I remember something like that?). One Indian guy who went to Cal. I guess it was a pretty racist audition, or I just don't remember any non-Caucasian/Asian people there.</p>\r\n<p>I felt plenty excited, but it was ten in the morning and I had no energy and probably could barely open my eyes (asian joke). And now I don't even remember what order things happened in; I think we took the test first. On the test, I got William and Harry mixed up, didn't know my cabinet members or who invented the internet, and guessed Falstaff for some random fat knight question. (Only the name occurred to me at this point--I was later inspired to read up on Falstaff simply because I'd guessed it here. Good stuff.)</p>\r\n<p>The interview (and the whole audition) might be one of my prouder moments in life. I successfully spent the entire three hours or so pretending to be a very well-adjusted extrovert. At the time I wasn't sure how successful I was (only in hindsight can I say I definitely did well), but I left feeling pretty comfortable that I'd made a nice impression. During the interview, I stood up straight, spoke loudly and clearly, made eye contact with Robert and Corina (ugh, eye contact), and cracked some random jokes. I riffed on using my hypothetical winnings to buy a trip to space; I still can't decide whether or not that's corny or brilliant. (Also later inspired to actually look up the prices of space trips--in the range of &gt;$250,000. Good thing no one there really knew either. And anyone who knows me knows that any prize money was going straight into the bank). Most other people did fine as well; I don't really want to mention it, but there were definitely a couple people who bombed the interview.</p>\r\n<p>Now that I think about it I might have succeeded precisely because I was an Asian guy trying to emulate outspoken white people. The other three or four Asian guys were all (ugh, stereotypically) meek and softspoken. Besides one Asian guy, whose interview I can't remember. I remember being worried about him, since he seemed pretty comfortable with talking and had a pretty good TV presence, until he said something undeniably and absurdly pretentious. He might have referred to himself as a genius or something along those lines. Sad that I can't remember.</p>\r\n<p>I left feeling like I did well. I got in the car and I told my family that my interview went great, and I was just unsure about my test results. But we knew it was a crapshoot from this point on. We collectively accepted that even if this was the last I ever heard from Jeopardy! (for this year), it was a worthwhile experience. We went to Chinatown, walked around, and got some food.</p>\r\n<p>I promptly forgot about the interview for the rest of the year. When I got back to Oregon and people asked when they could see me on TV, I told them not to wait. Within the week the whole thing passed out of my memory.</p>\r\n<p>(Man I want to write about the meatier things before I forget them this sucks)</p>",
