                "note_count": 3,
                "title": "Jeopardy!, Part 1",
                "body": "<p>I wish I&rsquo;d been putting down all my thoughts into words as this was going on, but I didn&rsquo;t. You don&rsquo;t really feel like posting when you&rsquo;ve got life to live, when the sun&rsquo;s shining and you feel effervescent. Then it&rsquo;s all over and you&rsquo;re sitting in front of your computer realizing that not only is it <em>finito</em>, you don&rsquo;t have any of the written record you&rsquo;d love to read five or ten years down the line. I&rsquo;m doing this mostly for myself, but maybe someone will want to read this.</p>\n<p>I got to play in the 2014 Jeopardy! College Championship. I placed third. I lost three games (all to the same person no less) and won once, and I&rsquo;m ecstatic that I did. I got my fifteen minutes of fame (at a pretty nice spot in my life, I&rsquo;d say), basked in a little bit of glory, and let all my grades deteriorate for two weeks. And I can&rsquo;t overstate the connect I feel with my fellow competitors, with all that we went through together. It&rsquo;s remarkable to think about what kind of bond 48 hours together can create. It really is the friendship I take away from the end that might mean more to me than the money (for sure) or the fame/notoriety (maybe. probably).</p>\n<p>I&rsquo;d could go on forever in this vein, gushing about the other competitors and probably unduly embarrassing myself. So I&rsquo;ll aim for chronological order.</p>\n<p>I took the online test in March. I was working on a CS project and while my partner and her roommates got dinner, I stayed in the room to take the test on her computer. It was quick. I figured I&rsquo;d done passably, and then promptly forgot about it.</p>\n<p>Got an e-mail in May inviting me down to LA for an audition. I was trepidatious about going; I&rsquo;d be in Oregon working during the audition, so I&rsquo;d have to take days off and fly down for a tiny shot at being on the show. But it wasn&rsquo;t really a choice for me to make. However I weighed the pros and cons, being on the show was a prize that vastly outweighed the poor odds or airfare.</p>\n<p>The other interns in Oregon were possibly more excited than I was. Like the CS partner, they immediately asked when they could expect to see me on the show. They all thought it was a sure thing, while I was almost certain I would flop&ndash;I&rsquo;d already convinced myself that flying down and just being in the audition was in itself a worthy experience. I&rsquo;m realizing right now my friends always expect more of me than I do myself, and I guess that&rsquo;s how I know they&rsquo;re my friends.</p>\n<p>But still, come on, my chances were tiny. I almost missed the train to the airport (thanks David Histing for getting me there on time), which in hindsight would have been absolutely tragic. I got to LA, met up with my sister and my mother who&rsquo;d driven down to meet me, and had a remarkably expensive dinner at Carl&rsquo;s Jr. after being unable to find an open restaurant at 9pm. I remember frantically spending the night trying to come up with stories that were somewhat unique and (just maybe) might resist being totally awkward. I tried to get some sleep, but nerves and a Law and Order marathon (you can&rsquo;t fall asleep in the middle of a show because you have to know how it ends, and each show starts immediately after the last, so until you hit a rerun you just have to keep watching) kept me up.</p>\n<p>I guess the audition deserves its own post at the rate I&rsquo;m going. I&rsquo;ll aim for this to be a ten-parter.</p>",
